The real missing piece in your architecture
You need a single canonical function that resolves current actor safely.
For example, conceptually:
current user = auth.uid()
current app context = app/account/session
current actor = resolved actor for that user in that app
RLS uses that actor
Without this, your RLS will always feel fragile because chat is neutral but your actors live in multiple app schemas.
Production recommendation
For your platform, I would lock this rule:
Rule 1
Every authenticated app session must carry one active actor_id in JWT/session claims.
Rule 2
That actor_id must come from the app’s actor model:
learning.actors.id
or vc.actors.id
Rule 3
All chat RLS uses only that resolved actor_id.
Rule 4
Chat controllers still enforce business meaning on top of RLS.
That is the cleanest way to make one neutral chat schema work across both apps.
In one sentence
Now that I’ve seen the full picture, the right way to build “real RLS” is:
resolve identity through auth.users and core.user_app_accounts, establish one active actor per session, and make all chat.* policies actor-membership based, while keeping multi-table chat writes inside the engine.
